      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "1c35e3afe90961b8",
      "text": "[[Thorsten Fuchshuber]],\n[[Meister der Rackets]].\nDie Russische Föderation unter der Herrschaft von Wladimir Putin\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7c412a57e5e4bf00",
      "text": "Some of his sentences are reminiscent of [[Carl Schmitt]]: \"If democracy means the disintegration of the state,\" [[Vladimir Putin]] said in September 2003 in an interview with correspondents of the Washington Post, \"then we don't need such a democracy. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7d5402fbe17e6bc0",
      "text": "The Russian president not only makes us think of Schmitt, because such a sentence could be effortlessly inserted into the thought structure of the counterrevolutionary theorist. The quoted sentence may also be considered paradigmatic in a very practical sense for the staging of a policy of the strong state, which has become known as the \"Putin system,\" and which can be reduced to the formula, analogous to Schmitt's theory of law: \"[[Sovereign]] is he who establishes order.\" "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "26d8600432eb9cab",
      "text": "This policy initially gives the impression that Putin's supposedly strong state stands against a disintegration of society into rackets, since the racket is associated, among other things, with the dissolution of the state, with warring gangs, and with the chaos of the \"unstate.\" It was just such a situation that Putin found himself in when he took office as President of the Russian Federation. Obviously, things have changed since then. But the question remains, what order did Putin create and by what means? And: Is Putin therefore an anti-racketeer?"
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0944f2fabc4b7e8d",
      "text": "His appointment to the presidency in 2000 was preceded by a development that, according to [[Walter Laqueur]], hardly allowed to distinguish \"between regular economic activity and the activities of the criminal underworld\". While it is doubtful that the extent and circumstances of these racket fights would ever become public, if they did, \"they could make the events of the era of the American robber barons seem comparatively like bickering in a kindergarten\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5d65fa0951ea2023",
      "text": "After President [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] had successively begun to reorient the Soviet Union from state-organized [[commodity]] production to market economy principles with various legislative initiatives since 1987, With the collapse of the USSR in 1991, a process of privatization began on the territory of the Russian Federation that emerged in the following years, in which the members of the old elite, the nomenklatura, were able to take over significant shares of the former Soviet production facilities. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7121981f6dc80ebb",
      "text": "Former apparatchiks and state dignitaries now became chairmen of supervisory boards and companies. The minister responsible for the privatization process at the time was quoted as saying that former state property simply belonged to those closest to him. What had previously been under the control of the nomenklatura now officially passed into the hands of former party migrants with title to ownership: \"Within a few years after the 1991 collapse, Russia's wealthiest were former members of the Communist elite. This group enjoyed an advantage because of its links to the old power structures.\" Moreover, they were in the best position to assess the potential of the companies to be appropriated on the world market, and thus knew which companies were likely to remain lucrative and which were not; all of them passed into private hands at ridiculous prices in relation to their real market value."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4187fff1f1bbcfaf",
      "text": "The Russian mafia was also involved and, according to [[Alfredo Schulte-Bockholt]], who has studied the interaction or amalgamation of political and criminal structures in Russia before and after the end of the Soviet Union, had a not inconsiderable influence on the fact that the rule of law, despite its anchoring in the 1993 constitution, was difficult to implement in legal practice in the early years. According to him, the infiltration of the power structures within the former Soviet states by the mafia not only delayed economic reforms, but also led to the fact that legal companies were downright forced to cooperate with the mafia. The weakness of the state became increasingly apparent."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4f8a683b38164336",
      "text": "The 'redistribution' of former Soviet state property cannot be seen without further ado in the sense of a \"so-called original accumulation\" (Marx) as the starting point for the emergence of a Russian national economy organized in private enterprise. Schulte-Bockholt, who has studied the entanglement of political elites and so-called organized crime, concludes: \"While most of the criminal organizations examined here have contributed to their respective national economies, Soviet crime groups have generally pillaged theirs – as do their post-Soviet successors.\" And indeed, in the years following the end of the Soviet Union, the gross domestic product plummeted: In 1998, it was only 57.3 percent of the 1990 GDP. It was only after Putin took office that there was a significant recovery; between 2000 and 2005, GDP rose from 67.1 to 90.4 percent of the 1990 level."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4f661e12ee7fd20b",
      "text": "What remained of the Soviet Union was in danger of being lost in the scramble for the spoils of competing power factions. Although the government under [[Boris Yeltsin]] attempted to implement a neo-liberal market economy and, with the constitution of 1993, comprehensive rule-of-law principles, the state as a whole proved too weak to guarantee their implementation in the long term."
    },
