      "type": "edit",
      "id": "7c412a57e5e4bf00",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "7c412a57e5e4bf00",
        "text": "Some of his sentences are reminiscent of Carl Schmitt: \"If democracy means the disintegration of the state,\" Vladimir Putin said in September 2003 in an interview with correspondents of the Washington Post, \"then we don't need such a democracy. The Russian president not only makes us think of Schmitt, because such a sentence could be effortlessly inserted into the thought structure of the counterrevolutionary theorist.3 The quoted sentence may also be considered paradigmatic in a very practical sense for the staging of a policy of the strong state, which has become known as the \"Putin system,\" and which can be reduced to the formula, analogous to Schmitt's theory of law: \"Sovereign is he who establishes order. \"4 This policy initially gives the impression that Putin's supposedly strong state stands against a disintegration of society into rackets, since the racket is associated, among other things, with the dissolution of the state, with warring gangs, and with the chaos of the \"unstate.\" It was just such a situation that Putin found himself in when he took office as President of the Russian Federation. Obviously, things have changed since then. But the question remains, what order did Putin create and by what means? And: Is Putin therefore an anti-racketeer?"
      },
      "date": 1647931427915
    },
