      "id": "0944f2fabc4b7e8d",
      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "0944f2fabc4b7e8d",
        "text": "His appointment to the presidency in 2000 was preceded by a development that, according to Walter Laqueur, hardly allowed to distinguish \"between regular economic activity and the activities of the criminal underworld \"5. While it is doubtful that the extent and circumstances of these racket fights would ever become public, if they did, \"they could make the events of the era of the American robber barons seem comparatively like bickering in a kindergarten \"6. After President Mikhail Gorbachev had successively begun to reorient the Soviet Union from state-organized commodity production to market economy principles with various legislative initiatives since 1987, With the collapse of the USSR in 1991, a process of privatization began on the territory of the Russian Federation that emerged in the following years, in which the members of the old elite, the nomenklatura, were able to take over significant shares of the former Soviet production facilities7. Former apparatchiks and state dignitaries now became chairmen of supervisory boards and companies. The minister responsible for the privatization process at the time was quoted as saying that former state property simply belonged to those closest to him.8 What had previously been under the control of the nomenklatura now officially passed into the hands of former party migrants with title to ownership: \"Within a few years after the 1991 collapse, Russia's wealthiest were former members of the Communist elite. This group enjoyed an advantage because of its links to the old power structures. \"9 Moreover, they were in the best position to assess the potential of the companies to be appropriated on the world market, and thus knew which companies were likely to remain lucrative and which were not;10 all of them passed into private hands at ridiculous prices in relation to their real market value.11 Translated with www.DeepL.com/Translator (free version)"
