        "id": "5d65fa0951ea2023",
        "text": "After President [[Mikhail Gorbachev]] had successively begun to reorient the Soviet Union from state-organized commodity production to market economy principles with various legislative initiatives since 1987, With the collapse of the USSR in 1991, a process of privatization began on the territory of the Russian Federation that emerged in the following years, in which the members of the old elite, the nomenklatura, were able to take over significant shares of the former Soviet production facilities7. Former apparatchiks and state dignitaries now became chairmen of supervisory boards and companies. The minister responsible for the privatization process at the time was quoted as saying that former state property simply belonged to those closest to him.8 What had previously been under the control of the nomenklatura now officially passed into the hands of former party migrants with title to ownership: \"Within a few years after the 1991 collapse, Russia's wealthiest were former members of the Communist elite. This group enjoyed an advantage because of its links to the old power structures. \"9 Moreover, they were in the best position to assess the potential of the companies to be appropriated on the world market, and thus knew which companies were likely to remain lucrative and which were not;10 all of them passed into private hands at ridiculous prices in relation to their real market value.11 "
