      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "4f8a683b38164336",
        "text": "The 'redistribution' of former Soviet state property cannot be seen without further ado in the sense of a \"so-called original accumulation\" (Marx) as the starting point for the emergence of a Russian national economy organized in private enterprise. Schulte-Bockholt, who has studied the entanglement of political elites and so-called organized crime, concludes: \"While most of the criminal organizations examined here have contributed to their respective national economies, Soviet crime groups have generally pillaged theirs - as do their post-Soviet successors.\" And indeed, in the years following the end of the Soviet Union, the gross domestic product plummeted: In 1998, it was only 57.3 percent of the 1990 GDP. It was only after Putin took office that there was a significant recovery; between 2000 and 2005, GDP rose from 67.1 to 90.4 percent of the 1990 level.15"
